# MODIS Fire Chronology — Run Card

This card shows the exact commands needed to run the pipeline from the command line.

---

## 0. Activate environment

### Conda (recommended)
```bash
conda activate mcd64a1

Verify GDAL has HDF4 support:
```bash
gdalinfo --formats | grep HDF

1. Go to repository root
cd path/to/modis-fire-chronology


(You must be in the repo root so scripts/ is found.)

2. Run extraction (per-buffer CSVs)
Example: run year 2020 (all regions, all months found on disk)
Windows
python scripts\extract_mcd64a1.py --years 2020

Linux / macOS
python scripts/extract_mcd64a1.py --years 2020

Optional flags
--years        2020 2021 2022
--months       03.01 04.01 05.01 06.01 07.01 08.01 09.01 10.01
--regions      Europe Siberia NorthAmerica
--hdf-root     <path to MODIS HDF root>
--out-root     <path to output_csvs>

Example: explicit regions
python scripts/extract_mcd64a1.py \
  --years 2020 \
  --regions Europe Siberia NorthAmerica

3. Run aggregation (yearly master tables)
Example: aggregate year 2020
Windows
python scripts\aggregate_fire_chronology.py --years 2020

Linux / macOS
python scripts/aggregate_fire_chronology.py --years 2020

Optional aggregation filters
--years   2020 2021
--months  3 4 5 6 7 8 9 10

4. Outputs
After extraction

Per-buffer CSVs written under:

<OUTPUT_ROOT>/<year>/<year>.<month>/<region>/A<BufferSize>/<scale>/*.csv

After aggregation

One CSV per year written to:

<OUTPUT_ROOT>/summaries/buffer_monthly_<YEAR>_master.csv


Example:

buffer_monthly_2020_master.csv

5. Expected console behavior

Tiles with no burned pixels → skipped

Buffers not intersecting a tile → skipped

Re-running the same year overwrites outputs

No severity, no attribution, no modeling — chronology only

6. Stop conditions (by design)

The pipeline stops at:

Burned area chronology

Temporal ranges and medians

Land-only normalization (% land burned)

No ecological or causal interpretation is performed.
